<!-- Do not remove this line! --> '''Emna Belhadj Yahia''' or '''Emna Belhaj Yahia''' ([[Arabic]]: آمنة بلحاج يحي) was born on September 30, 1945 in Tunis. She is a Tunisian teacher, philosopher and writer in French.
== Biography == Born on September 30, 1945 in [[Tunis]], from a family of theologians by her mother as well as from a family of wealthy traders by her father. She studied Philosophy in France, then obtained a diploma of high studies in Philosophy at [[Faculté des lettres de Paris|the faculty of Letters in Paris]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Bobin|first=Frédéric|date=September 25, 2015|title=Emna Belhaj Yahia listens to the torment of the Tunisian soul|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/international/article/2015/09/25/emna-belhaj-yahia-a-l-ecoute-des-tourments-de-l-ame-tunisienne_4771737_3210.html#bR71EHxACv6q71ba.99|journal=Le Monde|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> She enrolled as PhD student at "[[École pratique des hautes études|l'École pratique des hautes études]]", with [[Jacques Berque]], but she did not finish this course. The events of [[May 68|May '68]] took place simultaneously at her university trip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rencontres-et-debats-autrement.org/index.php?page=emna-belhaj-yahia|title=Emna Belhaj Yahia. Tunisia, between revolution and Islam|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>
Afterwards, she taught Philosophy a few years in Tunisia, before being the scientific director at the [[Tunisian Academy of Sciences, Letters, and Arts|Tunisian Academy of Sciences, Letters and Arts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.institutfrancais-tunisie.com/?q%3Dnode/8084|title=Prix Edgar Faure 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731014427/http://www.institutfrancais-tunisie.com/?q=node/8084 |archive-date=2017-07-31|dead-url=yes|access-date=}}</ref> She was also a member of a [[Feminism|feminist]] group, and later of the Tunisian League for Human Rights, before devoting herself to writing.<ref name=":1" /> After the [[Tunisian Revolution]] of 2011, and the years that followed, the rise of conservative [[Ennahda Movement|religious parties]] and the questioning by these parties of certain freedoms acquired by women, she decided to formalize her thoughts as well as critics in her book "''Tunisie, questions à mon pays" (Tunisia, questions to my country)'' in 2014<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Bouaouina|first=Kamel|date=June 10, 2014|title=Tunisia, questions to my country, from Emna Belhaj Yahia|url=|journal=Le Temps|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>''.''
